[Student "S"]
{South is to play 4\S. West leads the \DQ.  

Unless West is real beginner East will hold the \DA so you should not try the \DK on this trick. And when West continues with the \DJ you should again duck in dummy, ruffing with an honor in your hand.

The contract is in danger if East holds the \CA because you would have three \C losers to go with the \D already lost. One really good possibility is that East now has the lone \DA and you can set up dummy's \DK with a ruff.

So play a small \S to dummy's \S9, (pulling the two outstanding trumps), and ruff another \D with an honor, hoping the \DA drops.

Too bad, the \DA did not fall so dummy's \DK is not a winner. But it will still prove to be useful. 

Play the \HA, then ruff a \H in dummy. Play a trump to your \SA and ruff your last \H.

You are in dummy, just where you want to be. Play the \DK, and when East plays the \DA don't ruff but instead discard a \C from your hand. You knew all along that he held the \DA.

[showcards N:SJ,CK,C5,C3 S:S6,S3,C7,C6]

East is end-played, forced to either break the \Cs and give you a \C trick, or give you a ruff-sluff.

This was the toughest hand so far and the end-play depended upon your correct reading that East must hold the \DA.

It also depended upon the defenders not switching to \Cs at the second trick. If West had decided to switch to the \CQ you would have had no chance at all. }
[Play "W"]DQ

